Cardiff University

Welcome to Cardiff University

We hope you will enjoy the open day, of everything we have to offer. You will get to know about all the places around the university, from different schools of courses to residence halls. You will also be able to visit the student union for events to be shown from private societal events to big nightclubs.

Have a look at the list of venues, tours and events available between 9am and 5pm on 5th July 2019.

There will be plenty of time to ask questions and it’s the ideal way to find out more about the academic and social facilities in different areas of the campus. Each tour lasts approximately 45 minutes.

Please note that we are also offering tours of the Cathays Park Campus in Welsh at 10.00am and 1.00pm.		 A student-guided 45 minute walking tour around the campus. Horseshoe Drive, front of Main Building 3 51.48783 -3.178182 1 Main Building (Park Place) Main Building - Architect W.D. Caroe sought to combine the charm and elegance of his former college (Trinity College, Cambridge) with the picturesque balance of many of the University of Oxford colleges. Building work on the Main Building commenced in 1905 and was completed in many stages, the first in 1909. Money ran short for this project, however, and although the side-wings were completed in the 1960s the planned Great Hall has never been built.

 Park Place CF10 3AT 1 https://opendaydata.cardiff.ac.uk/images/locations/MainBuilding.jpg https://www.cardiff.ac.uk/visit/accessibility/cathays-park-campus/main-building 1 0 1 2 1 3 Talk #ebe9e1 false 2802 7 43 38 5 2019-07-05 10:00:00 2019-07-05 16:00:00 Widening Participation Drop-in Session We offer support to a wide range of under-represented groups in Higher Education prior to applying to university, including:
- Asylum Seekers
- Looked after Children and Care Leavers
- Estranged Students
- Forces Veterans
- Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans(gender)
- Mature Students
- Student Carers
- Student Parents

If you fall under one of these categories please feel free to drop in and meet with the Widening Participation Team, we can provide:
- Individual pathway planning to help you make important decisions about university
- Tailored advice on making the most out of an Open Day
- Support and advice on the process of applying to university
 Drop-in support for students from under-represented groups. Ground Floor Foyer, Hadyn Ellis Building 43 51.492214 -3.18295 1 Hadyn Ellis Building The Hadyn Ellis building is named in honour of the late University Deputy Vice-Chancellor, Professor Hadyn Ellis. The ground floor includes an attractive public area for lectures, displays and conferences about the University’s work and a 150-person lecture theatre. The building has been recognised for its sustainability and was awarded the Higher Education category of the Building Research Establishment Environmental Assessment Method BREEAM) Awards Wales in 2012.

Wallace Lecture Theatre 3 51.48783 -3.178182 1 Main Building (Park Place) Main Building - Architect W.D. Caroe sought to combine the charm and elegance of his former college (Trinity College, Cambridge) with the picturesque balance of many of the University of Oxford colleges. Building work on the Main Building commenced in 1905 and was completed in many stages, the first in 1909. Money ran short for this project, however, and although the side-wings were completed in the 1960s the planned Great Hall has never been built.

Settling in and making new friends are important first steps in university life. With 16 different residences providing in excess of 5,500 study bedrooms, Cardiff students can apply for the residences which best suit their particular preferences and, unusually for a civic university, the residences are within walking distance of the main campus and city centre. Ground Floor Chemistry Foyer 3 51.48783 -3.178182 1 Main Building (Park Place) Main Building - Architect W.D. Caroe sought to combine the charm and elegance of his former college (Trinity College, Cambridge) with the picturesque balance of many of the University of Oxford colleges. Building work on the Main Building commenced in 1905 and was completed in many stages, the first in 1909. Money ran short for this project, however, and although the side-wings were completed in the 1960s the planned Great Hall has never been built.

The School of Journalism, Media and Culture is located opposite Cardiff Central Train Station and is approximately 20-30 minutes on foot from the Cathays Park Campus. If you are travelling by train, you may wish to plan your day in advance and consider visiting the School on arrival at Cardiff Central, or on your return to the station.

Advice and support for students Music Building 13 51.4892 -3.1834388 1 Music Building As you approach the School of Music, you can’t fail to notice the bronze sculpture on the lawn outside. We often get asked about this artwork so here’s a little background on it. The piece is called Three Obliques (Walk-In) and was created by the famed artist Dame Barbara Hepworth in 1968. Only two others exist, one at Chatsworth House, and one in Seattle. It’s an astonishing piece of sculpture and provides a lovely backdrop for our annual graduation photos!
